reviewText: This DVD is clearly identified as Tim Conway television material from the 1960s - as the photo in the artwork alsoreveals - so anyone expecting more "modern" footage - as some reviewers complained - just aren't paying attentionto what they are buying.Understandably, this is historic footage of the funny man in his early TV days honing his humorous craft. For the price itis certainly a bargain and great to see some of the routines he talks about in his new printed autobiography in 2013.
summary: GREAT EARLY CONWAY COMEDY ROUTINES FROM THE 1960s

reviewText: Tim was a great comedian, but a lot of his goofiness doesn't go across the generation gap well.  Most of the co-stars he had on with him were from a generation that is no longer with us.  It would have been helpful is we had some text to be able to identy the stars that the audience was so obviously in love with.  I gave it to a man in the generation ahead of me, and he loved it.
summary: Timeless, but not for the younger generation

reviewText: This is Tim from the early 50s to the mid 60s? Before his days on Carol Burnett. Tim's strength is his physical comedy & spontaneous witty ad-lib. He also does best when another actor tries to hold in a laugh at his jokes & that gives Tim confidence to do what he does best & go off the script. That barely happens once in this hour program when a ringing phone didn't happen & he pretending to be psychic (I forget) & the other actor died laughing. I wished Tim kept going, but he went back to the script. All stage skit material from different variety shows, many of them having Tim play a character called "Dag Hartford" as a jockey, car driver, hippie, caveman, etc. It's the same character, the type that's slow, thick-headed, etc. But nowhere near as good as his days on Carol. There's almost no physical comedy as well.
summary: Older sketch comedy before Carol Burnette days
